# Architecture & Component Structure

{{#if isNestJS}}
This project uses NestJS. All business logic must be encapsulated in Feature Modules.

## NestJS Module Structure
- Features belong in `src/modules/<feature-name>/`
- Register all controllers, services, and repositories in the feature module (`<feature>.module.ts`).
- Ensure the module exports services that other modules need, rather than importing raw services across feature boundaries.

## Dependency Injection (DI)
Use constructor-based injection.
```typescript
constructor(
  private readonly userService: UserService,
  private readonly configService: ConfigService,
) {}
```
{{else if isExpress}}
This project uses Express.

## Router & Middleware Structure
- Group related routes into sub-routers in `src/routes/` or feature-based folders like `src/api/<feature>/`.
- Mount feature routers in your main `app.ts` or `server.ts`.
- Use Express middleware for cross-cutting concerns (auth, logging) rather than duplicating logic in handlers.
{{else if isFastify}}
This project uses Fastify.

## Plugin Ecosystem
- Use `fastify-plugin` (`fp`) to share decorators, hooks, and services across plugins.
- Group related routes into feature plugins.
- Keep the `server.js` or `app.js` entry point minimal, delegating to encapsulated plugins.
{{else if isHono}}
This project uses Hono.

## App & Group Structure
- Group routes using Hono's `.route()` method for modularity.
- Place feature-specific handlers in `src/api/<feature>/`.
- Use built-in middleware when possible or write custom middleware using `c.next()`.
{{/if}}

## Repository Pattern
{{> repositoryPattern }}

## General App Architecture
- **Controllers/Handlers:** Parse requests, call services, format responses. No complex business logic.
- **Services:** Pure business logic. They do not know about HTTP requests or responses.
- **Repositories:** Data access layer. Handles all direct DB/ORM calls.
- **Global Pipes/Interceptors/Middleware:** Use for authentication, request logging, and global error catch-alls.

## Graceful Shutdown
Always ensure the HTTP server and database connections close gracefully on SIGTERM and SIGINT signals to avoid dropping requests during deployments.
